==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sounder</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Soundest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sound</ets>, AS.
<ets>sund</ets>; akin to D. ge<ets>zond</ets>, G. ge<ets>sund</ets>,
OHG. gi<ets>sunt</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>sund</ets>, and perhaps to L.
<ets>sanus</ets>. Cf. <er>Sane</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Whole;
unbroken; unharmed; free from flaw, defect, or decay; perfect of the
kind; <as>as, <ex>sound</ex> timber; <ex>sound</ex> fruit; a
<ex>sound</ex> tooth; a <ex>sound</ex> ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Healthy; not diseased; not being in a morbid state;
-- said of body or mind; <as>as, a <ex>sound</ex> body; a <ex>sound</ex>
constitution; a <ex>sound</ex> understanding</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Firm; strong; safe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The brasswork here, how rich it is in beams,⟦br⟧
And how, besides, it makes the whole house <qex>sound</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Free from error; correct; right; honest; true;
faithful; orthodox; -- said of persons; <as>as, a <ex>sound</ex> lawyer;
a <ex>sound</ex> thinker</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do not I know you a favorer⟦br⟧
Of this new seat? Ye are nor <qex>sound</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Founded in truth or right; supported by justice; not
to be overthrown on refuted; not fallacious; <as>as, <ex>sound</ex>
argument or reasoning; a <ex>sound</ex> objection; <ex>sound</ex>
doctrine; <ex>sound</ex> principles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hold fast the form of <qex>sound</qex> words, which thou hast
heard of me.</q> <rj><qau>2 Tim. i. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>heavy; laid on with force; <as>as, a <ex>sound</ex>
beating</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Undisturbed; deep; profound; <as>as, <ex>sound</ex>
sleep</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Founded in law; legal; valid; not defective; <as>as,
a <ex>sound</ex> title to land</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Sound</xex> is sometimes used in the formation of
self-explaining compounds; as, <xex>sound</xex>-headed,
<xex>sound</xex>-hearted, <xex>sound</xex>-timbered, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sound currency</b></col> <fld>(Com.)</fld>, <cd>a
currency whose actual value is the same as its nominal value; a currency
which does not deteriorate or depreciate or fluctuate in comparision
with the standard of values.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Soundly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So <qex>sound</qex> he slept that naught might him awake.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>sund</ets> a narrow sea or
strait; akin to Icel., Sw., Dan. & G. <ets>sund</ets>, probably so named
because it could be <ets>swum</ets> across. See <er>Swim</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Geog.)</fld> <def>A narrow passage of water, or a strait between
the mainland and an island; also, a strait connecting two seas, or
connecting a sea or lake with the ocean; <as>as, the <ex>Sound</ex>
between the Baltic and the german Ocean; Long Island
<ex>Sound</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>Sound</qex> of Denmark, where ships pay toll.</q>
<rj><qau>Camden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sound dues</b></col>, <cd>tolls formerly imposed by
Denmark on vessels passing through the Baltic Sound.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sounded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sounding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>sonder</ets>; cf. AS.
<ets>sund</ets>gyrd a sounding rod, <ets>sund</ets>line a sounding line
(see <er>Sound</er> a narrow passage of water).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To measure the depth of; to fathom; especially, to ascertain the
depth of by means of a line and plummet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To ascertain, or try to ascertain, the
thoughts, motives, and purposes of (a person); to examine; to try; to
test; to probe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was in jest,⟦br⟧
And by that offer meant to <qex>sound</qex> your breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I've <qex>sounded</qex> my Numidians man by man.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To explore, as the bladder or
urethra, with a sound; to examine with a sound; also, to examine by
auscultation or percussion; <as>as, to <ex>sound</ex> a
patient</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1375 --></p>

<p><ent>Sound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To ascertain the
depth of water with a sounding line or other device.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>sound</qex> as a shipman <qex>soundeth</qex> in the sea
with his plummet to know the depth of sea.</q>
<rj><qau>Palsgrave.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 8 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>sonde</ets>. See
<er>Sound</er> to fathom.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Any elongated
instrument or probe, usually metallic, by which cavities of the body are
sounded or explored, especially the bladder for stone, or the urethra
for a stricture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 9 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>soun</ets>, OF.
<ets>son</ets>, <ets>sun</ets>, F. <ets>son</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>sonus</ets> akin to Skr. <ets>svana</ets> sound, <ets>svan</ets> to
sound, and perh. to E. <ets>swan</ets>. Cf. <er>Assonant</er>,
<er>Consonant</er>, <er>Person</er>, <er>Sonata</er>, <er>Sonnet</er>,
<er>Sonorous</er>, <er>Swan</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The peceived
object occasioned by the impulse or vibration of a material substance
affecting the ear; a sensation or perception of the mind received
through the ear, and produced by the impulse or vibration of the air or
other medium with which the ear is in contact; the effect of an
impression made on the organs of hearing by an impulse or vibration of
the air caused by a collision of bodies, or by other means; noise;
report; <as>as, the <ex>sound</ex> of a drum; the <ex>sound</ex> of the
human voice; a horrid <ex>sound</ex>; a charming <ex>sound</ex>; a
sharp, high, or shrill <ex>sound</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The warlike <qex>sound</qex>⟦br⟧
Of trumpets loud and clarions.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The occasion of sound; the impulse or vibration
which would occasion sound to a percipient if present with unimpaired;
hence, the theory of vibrations in elastic media such cause sound;
<as>as, a treatise on <ex>sound</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense, sounds are spoken of as
<xex>audible</xex> and <xex>inaudible</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Noise without signification; empty noise; noise and
nothing else.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sense and not <qex>sound</qex> . . . must be the principle.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sound boarding</b></col>, <cd>boards for holding pugging,
placed in partitions of under floors in order to deaden sounds.</cd> --
<col><b>Sound bow</b></col>, <cd>in a series of transverse sections of a
bell, that segment against which the clapper strikes, being the part
which is most efficacious in producing the sound. See <xex>Illust.</xex>
of <er>Bell</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sound post</b></col>.
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Sounding post</cref>, under
<er>Sounding</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 10 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sounen</ets>,
<ets>sownen</ets>, OF. <ets>soner</ets>, <ets>suner</ets>, F.
<ets>sonner</ets>, from L. <ets>sonare</ets>. See <er>Sound</er> a
noise.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a noise; to utter a voice; to
make an impulse of the air that shall strike the organs of hearing with
a perceptible effect.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧And first taught speaking trumpets
how to <xex>sound</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How silver-sweet <qex>sound</qex> lovers' tongues!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be conveyed in sound; to be spread or published;
to convey intelligence by sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From you <qex>sounded</qex> out the word of the Lord.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Thess. i. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make or convey a certain impression, or to have a
certain import, when heard; hence, to seem; to appear; <as>as, this
reproof <ex>sounds</ex> harsh; the story <ex>sounds</ex> like an
invention</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good sir, why do you start, and seem to fear⟦br⟧
Things that do <qex>sound</qex> so fair?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>To sound in</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To sound
into</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to tend to; to partake of the nature of; to
be consonant with.</cd> <mark>[Obs., except in the phrase To sound in
damages, below.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Soun[d]ing in</qex> moral virtue was his speech.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>To sound in damages</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>to
have the essential quality of damages. This is said of an action
brought, not for the recovery of a specific thing, as replevin, etc.,
but for damages only, as trespass, and the like.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Sound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 11 ====
HEADWORD: Sound
<hw>Sound</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to make a
noise; to play on; <as>as, to <ex>sound</ex> a trumpet or a horn; to
<ex>sound</ex> an alarm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A bagpipe well could he play and <qex>soun</qex>[d].</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to exit as a sound; <as>as, to
<ex>sound</ex> a note with the voice, or on an
instrument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To order, direct, indicate, or proclain by a sound,
or sounds; to give a signal for by a certain sound; <as>as, to
<ex>sound</ex> a retreat; to <ex>sound</ex> a parley</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The clock <qex>sounded</qex> the hour of noon.</q> <rj><qau>G. H.
Lewes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To celebrate or honor by sounds; to cause to be
reported; to publish or proclaim; <as>as, to <ex>sound</ex> the praises
of fame of a great man or a great exploit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To examine the condition of (anything) by causing
the same to emit sounds and noting their character; <as>as, to
<ex>sound</ex> a piece of timber; to <ex>sound</ex> a vase; to
<ex>sound</ex> the lungs of a patient</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To signify; to import; to denote.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Soun[d]ing</qex> alway the increase of his winning.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soundable</ent>⟦br⟧
